Scheme 1 Schematic representation of the synthesis of ligand (HL) and copper(I) complex 1. Table 1 The selected bond distances and angles for complex 1. Bond distances (Å) Cu(1)-Cu(1)#1 2.4764(8) Cu(1)-N(1) 1.902(3) Cu(1)-N(3) 1.902(3) N(1)-N(2) 1.309(4) N(2)-N(3) 1.297(4) Bond angles (°) N(3)-Cu(1)-N(1)#1 171.23(12) N(2)#1-N(3)#1-Cu(1)#1 127.1(2) N(2)-N(1)-Cu(1)#1 126.8(2) N(3)-N(2)-N(1) 114.6(2) A new copper(I)–triazenido electro-catalyst for catalyzing hydrogen evolution from acetic acid and water Ting Fang a Hai-Xia Lu a Jia-Xing Zhao a Shu-Zhong Zhan a ⁎ Qi-Ying Lv b ⁎ a College of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering, South China University of Technology, Guangzhou 510640, China College of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering, South China University of Technology Guangzhou 510640 China b School of Chemistry & Chemical Engineering, Huazhong University of Science and Technology, Wuhan 430074, China School of Chemistry & Chemical Engineering, Huazhong University of Science and Technology Wuhan 430074 China ⁎ Corresponding authors. Fax: +86 20 87112053. Graphical abstract The reaction of 2-chloroaniline and o-anisidine afforded a new triazenido ligand, 1-[(2-methoxy) benzene]-3-[2-(chloro)benzene] triazene (HL). In the presence of Et3N, the reaction of HL and CuI gave a triazenide complex {Cu2(L)2} 1, a new molecular electrocatalyst, which has been determined by X-ray crystallography. The CuCu distance of 2.4764(8) Å is significantly shorter than the sum of the van der Waals radii of Cu (1.40Å). Electrochemical studies indicated that the catalyst can catalyze hydrogen evolution from both acetic acid with a turnover frequency (TOF) of 65 (in DMF) moles of hydrogen per mole of catalyst per hour at an overpotential of 942mV and neutral buffer (pH 7.0) with a TOF of 324 moles of hydrogen per mole of catalyst per hour at an overpotential of 939mV vs SHE, respectively. Sustained proton reduction catalysis occurs at glassy carbon (GC) to give H2 over a 72h electrolysis period with 97% Faradaic yield and no observable decomposition of the catalyst. Keywords Dinuclear triazenido copper(I) complex Crystal structure Molecular catalyst Hydrogen evolution 1 Introduction Hydrogen has emerged as an attractive candidate for a clean, sustainable fuel and underpins the intense interest in creating artificial systems that use catalysts based on elements abundant in the Earth to achieve efficient hydrogen production from water [1–3]. In nature, enzymes can perform the hydrogen evolution reaction efficiently through nickel and iron cofactors, which evolve hydrogen catalytically near the thermodynamic potential with high turnover frequencies [4,5]. However, enzymes are difficult to obtain in sufficient amounts to adapt for commercial applications and their stability is often limited outside of their native environment [4–7]. These considerations have led to the development of molecular catalysts employing more abundant metals, and several complexes that contain nickel [8–13], cobalt [14–18], iron [19,20] and molybdenum [21,22] have been developed as electrocatalysts for the reduction of proton to form H2. However, an important fundamental question for the enzymes that remains to be answered is the precise role of the proposed pendant base in hydrogen oxidation and production. And most of the diiron dithiolate complexes have been electrochemically investigated by using organic acids in organic solvents. It has been shown that the donor type and electronic properties of the ligands play vital roles in determining the structure and reactivity of the corresponding metal complexes. Identification of the factors that control the oxidation/reduction site in these complexes, determining of their redox potentials and characterization of their electronic structures are critical for the design of more effective molecular electrocatalysts for H2 production. With this mind, our group has tried to probe new electro-catalysts through the synthesis of dinuclear complexes with new ligands. The central nitrogen of the triazenido ligand imparts greater basicity on the [N···N···N]− relative to the neutral nitrogen, making the triazenido more electron donating, amenable to binding to H+ and hydrogen production. And we chose triazenido ligands to assembly new complexes and explore their possible catalytic function [23–25]. As an expanded work, we present the synthesis, structure and properties of a new dinuclear triazenido-copper(I) complex [Cu2L2] 1, that can catalyze hydrogen evolution from acetic acid or water. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials and physical measurements All commercially available reagents were used as received without further purification. 1H NMR spectrum was measured on a Bruker AM 500 spectrometer in CDCl3. UV–Vis spectra were measured on a Hitachi U-3010. Cyclic voltammograms were obtained on a CHI-660E electrochemical analyzer under N2 using a three-electrode cell in which a glassy carbon electrode GC, 1mm in diameter) was the working electrode, a saturated Ag/AgNO3 electrode was the reference electrode, and platinum wire was the auxiliary electrode. A ferrocene/ferrocenium (1+) couple was used as an internal standard and E1/2 of the ferrocene/ferrocenium (Fc/Fc+) couple under the experimental condition was 0.50V. 0.1M [(n-Bu)4N]ClO4 was used as the supporting electrolyte. Acetic acid was added by syringe. Controlled-potential electrolysis (CPE) in DMF was conducted using an air-tight glass double compartment cell separated by a glass frit. The working compartment was fitted with a glassy carbon plate and an Ag/AgNO3 reference electrode. The auxiliary compartment was fitted with a Pt gauze electrode. The working compartment was filled with 50mL of 1.044mM acetic acid in a 0.1M [(n-Bu4N)]ClO4 DMF solution, while the auxiliary compartment was filled with 35mL of 0.1M [(n-Bu4N)]ClO4 DMF solution, resulting in equal solution levels in both compartments. Both compartments were sparged for 60min with N2 and cyclic voltammograms were recorded as controls. Complex 1 (3.0μM) was then added and a cyclic voltammogram was recorded. CPE in aqueous media was also conducted using an air-tight glass double compartment cell separated by a glass frit. The working compartment was fitted with a glassy carbon plate and an Ag/AgCl reference electrode. The auxiliary compartment was fitted with a Pt gauze electrode. The working compartment was filled with 50mL of 0.25M phosphate buffer solution (CH3CN:H2O=2:3 as solvent) at different pH values containing 0.1M KCl of the supporting electrolyte, while the auxiliary compartment was filled with 35mL dihydrogen phosphate buffer solution. Both compartments were sparged for 60min with N2 and cyclic voltammograms were recorded as controls. Complex 1 (2.47μM) was then added and a cyclic voltammogram was recorded. After electrolysis, a 0.5mL aliquot of the headspace was removed and replaced with 0.5mL of CH4. A sample of the headspace was injected into the gas chromatograph (GC). GC experiments were carried out with an Agilent Technologies 7890A gas chromatography instrument. 2.2 Synthesis of 1-[(2-methoxy) benzene]-3-[2-(chloro)benzene] triazene (HL) A solution of 2-chloroaniline (1.275g, 10mmol) in water (5ml) was mixed with 1molL−1 HCl 30ml (30mmol) at 0°C. An aqueous solution (15%) of sodium nitrite (15mmol) was added dropwise with stirring. Later, an equal amount of o-anisidine (1.23g, 10mmol) in ethanol was added with continuous stirring. The reaction mixture was neutralized with a 15% aqueous of NaCH3CO2 to give red precipitate. The reaction mixture was filtered, and the solid was purified by crystallization at −4°C from 9:1 ethyl acetate/hexanes to obtain red crystals, which were collected and dried in vacuo (1.62g, 62%). Calcd for C13H12ClN3O: C, 59.61; H, 4.59; N, 16.05%. Found C, 59.33; H, 4.58; N, 16.10. 1H NMR (CDCl3) δ 12.58 (s, 1H), 8.025 (d, J =3.0Hz, 1H), 7.94 (d, J =2.0Hz, 1H), 7.625 (d, J =3.0Hz, 1H), 7.54 (t, J =4.0Hz, 1H), 7.47 (d, J =2.0Hz, 1H), 7.30 (t, J =3Hz, 1H), 7.22 (t, J =4Hz, 1H), 7.06 (t, J =4Hz, 1H), 3.96 (s, 3H). UV–vis [CH3CN, λ max/nm (ɛ/Lmol−1 cm−1)]: 202 (2.75×103), 240 (1.1×103), 368 (1.37×103). 2.3 Synthesis of complex 1 To a solution, containing HL (0.131g, 0.5mmol) and triethylamine (0.05g, 0.5mmol)) in acetonitrile/tetrahydrofuran (10mL, 1:1), CuI (0.095g, 0.5mmol) was added and the mixture was stirred for 3min. Single crystals were obtained from the filtrate which was allowed to stand at room temperature for several days, collected by filtration, and dried in vacuo (0.08g, 49.4%). The elemental analysis results (Found C, 48.51; H, 3.38; N, 12.99. C26H22Cl2Cu2N6O2 requires C, 48.11; H, 3.39; N, 12.95) were in agreement with the formula of the sample used for X-ray analysis. UV–vis [CH3CN, λ max/nm (ɛ/Lmol−1 cm−1)]: 207 (2.78×103), 248 (1.05×103), 383 (1.13×103), 500 (330). 2.4 Crystal structure determination The X-ray analysis of 1 was carried out with a Bruker SMART CCD area detector using graphite monochromated Mo-Kα Radiation (λ =0.71073Å) at room temperature. All empirical absorption corrections were applied by using the SADABS program [26]. The structure was solved using direct methods and the corresponding non-hydrogen atoms are refined anisotropically. All the hydrogen atoms of the ligands were placed in calculated positions with fixed isotropic thermal parameters and included in the structure factor calculations in the final stage of full-matrix least-squares refinement. All calculations were performed using the SHELXTL computer program [27]. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Synthesis and characterization As shown in Scheme 1 , 1-[(2-methoxy) benzene]-3-[2-(chloro)benzene] triazene (HL) was synthesized by the reaction of 2-chloroaniline and o-anisidine anthranilate in 62% yield. 1H resonances were found at 12.58ppm for a singlet of triazene group hydrogen atom, and in the range of 8.10–7.00ppm for the aromatic protons (supporting information, Fig. S1). Complex 1 was obtained as red crystals by the reaction of HL and CuI in acetonitrile/tetrahydrofuran in 49.4% yield. The electronic spectra of HL and 1 were recorded in CH3CN (Fig. S2). HL mainly exhibits three bands at 202, 240 and 368nm, and complex 1 exhibits four bands at 207, 248, 383 and 500nm. Compared with that of HL (368nm), the absorption maxima of the low-energy band of complex 1 (383nm) is red-shifted to a longer-wavelength region. This is assignable to intraligand transitions of the L− ligands, as well as a M→L MLCT transition from the Cu(I) ion to the deprotonated ligand (L−). 3.2 Structural analysis Single crystal X-ray diffraction analysis of the complex revealed the solid state structure of the complex to be a di-copper complex [Cu2(L)2]. Table S1 listed details of the crystal parameters, data collection and refinements for complex 1. Table 1 listed the selected bond distances and angles for 1. The molecular structure of the complex [Cu2(L)2] is depicted in Fig. 1 . The copper complex [Cu2(L)2] is isotypic, and share many of the gross structural features of previously structurally characterized Cu(I) di-metallic systems [28–30], consisting of two metal centers bridged by two triazenide ligands in an μ, η1, η1-fashion, with approximately linear two coordinate geometries [N(1)#1-Cu(1)-N(3): 171.23(12)o], with the deviation caused by the metal atoms moving away from each other. Copper complex 1 is formed by the two N3-ligands and the {Cu2} unit. The Cu-N bond distances in [Cu2(L)2] are within the expected ranges for terminal Cu(I) N bonds [CuN: 1.902(3) Å [29,30]. Similarly the NN bond lengths within the triazenide ligands [N(1)-N(2): 1.309(4) Å, N(2)-N(3): 1.297(4) Å in [Cu2(L)2] are also comparable to those observed in related systems [28–30]. A significant point of interest in 1 is the presence of relatively short M···M intramolecular distance. The Cu-Cu distance of 2.4764(8) Å is significantly shorter than the sum of the van der Waals radii [31] of Cu (1.40Å). 3.3 Electrochemical studies Cyclic voltammogram of complex 1 in DMF was measured at a glassy carbon electrode (1mm diameter) in the presence of 0.1M [n-Bu4N]ClO4 as supporting electrolyte. All potentials in this study were given versus the FeCP2 +/0 couple internal standard. As shown in Fig. S3, cyclic voltammogram of complex 1 exhibits two quasi-reversible waves at −1.04V and −1.59V versus Ag/AgNO3, which can be assigned to CuII/I and CuI/0 couples, respectively. As observed in Fig. S4, the current responses of the redox events at −1.59V show linear dependence on the square root of the scan rate, which is an indicative of a diffusion-controlled process, with the electrochemically active species freely diffusing in the solution. Such distinctive potential prompts possible usage of this complex as an electrocatalyst for hydrogen evolution reaction. 3.4 Catalytic hydrogen evolution in DMF To determine possible electrocatalytic activity of this complex, cyclic voltammograms of complex 1 were recorded in the presence of acetic acid. Fig. 2 showed a systematic increase in i cat observed near −1.32V with increasing acid concentration from 0.43 to 52.2mM. This rise in current can be attributed to the catalytic generation of H2 from acetic acid [21], with catalytic onset shift to more positive potentials (from −1.42 to −1.33V). The onset of catalytic current moved to more anodic values and the height of catalytic current increases with the sequential increments of acid concentration. Based on Eq. (1), this reduction occurred at an overpotential of 382mV. (1) E HA ⊙ = E H ⊙ - + ( 2.303 R T / F ) p K a HA A number of control experiments were carried out to verify that complex 1 is responsible for the catalysis. In particular, acetic acid, the free ligand, CuI, the mixture of the free ligand and CuI, and the mixture of the free ligand, CuI and acetic acid were each measured under identical conditions. As can be seen in Fig. S5– S9, the catalytic competency achieved with 1 is not matched by just ligand, CuCl, or the mixture of the free ligand and CuCl, as might arise from dissociation of the ligand, nor can it be accomplished with the ligand bound to a redox-inactive metal. Thus, a combination of the redox-active Cu ion and the ligand is essential for catalytic activity. Further evidence for the electro-catalytic activity was obtained by bulk electrolysis of a DMF solution of complex 1 (3.0μM) with acetic acid (3.12mM) at variable overpotentials using a glassy carbon plate electrode in a double-compartment cell. A series of applied potentials were chosen, corresponding to the electro-catalytic potentials observed in cyclic voltmmograms. Fig. 3(a) shows the total charge of bulk electrolysis of complex 1 in the presence of acid, the charge significantly increased when the overpotentials was adding. Assuming every catalyst molecule was distributed on the electrode surface and every electron was used for the reduction of protons. According to Eq. (2) [21], we calculated TOF for the catalyst reaching a maximum of 65 moles of hydrogen per mole of catalyst per hour (see supported materials-Eq. (3) and Fig. 3(b)). (2) TOF = Δ C / ( F * n 1 * n 2 * t ) Where, ΔC is the charge from catalyst solution during CPE minus charge from solution without catalyst during CPE, F is the Faraday's constant, n 1 is the mol of electrons required to generate a mol of H2, n 2 is the mol of catalyst in solution, t is duration of electrolysis. 3.5 Catalytic hydrogen evolution in aqueous media We also tried to explore the catalytic hydrogen evolution in aqueous media, a much more attractive medium for the sustainable generation of hydrogen. CVs were conducted in 0.25M phosphate buffers at different pH values. As shown in Fig. 4 , in the absence of complex 1, a catalytic current was not apparent until a potential of −1.5V versus Ag/AgCl was attained. With addition of complex 1, the onset of catalytic current was observed at about −1.2V versus Ag/AgCl, and the current strength increased significantly with increasing concentrations of complex 1 from 0.00 to 0.031mM. When concentration of complex 1 reached 0.031mM, the potential at −1.1V and current strength did not change obviously. The potential moved positive about 400mV compared to that in the absence of complex 1. Furthermore, it was found that the catalytic current maximum of 1 was also dependent on pH values of buffers (Fig. S10), indicating this catalyst is functioning in a diffusion-controlled regime and is molecular in nature. Catalytic hydrogen production can also be achieved with complex 1 in buffer, Fig. 5 shows the total charge of bulk electrolysis of the solution containing complex 1 at pH 7.0. When the overpotential was 839mV versus SHE at pH 7.0, the maximum charge was only 56.5mC during 2min of electrolysis in absence of complex 1 (Fig. S11). Under the same conditions, the charge reached 262.7mC with addition of complex 1 (2.47μM), accompanying the formation of gas, which was confirmed to be H2 by GC analysis. The evolved H2 was analyzed by gas chromatography, Fig. 6(a), which gave ∼14.6mL of H2 over an electrolysis period of 1h with a Faradaic efficiency of 97% for H2 (Fig. 6(b)). Based on Eq. (2), the TOF for complex 1 are 324 (see supported materials-Eq. (4)) and 272 (pH 7.0) moles of hydrogen per mole of catalyst per hour at overpotentials of 939, and 839mV vs SHE, respectively (Fig. 5(b)). To the best of our knowledge, this value (272moles/h) is significantly higher than some reported molecular catalysts for electrochemical hydrogen production from neutral water, including a dinickel complex that exhibits a turnover number of 100 moles of H2 per mole of catalyst with a turnover frequency of 160 moles of H2 per mole of catalyst per hour at an overpotential of 820mV [32] and a cobalt complex displaying a turnover number of 5 moles of H2 per mole of catalyst with a turnover number of 0.4 moles of H2 per mole of catalyst per hour at an overpotential of 390mV [33], yet smaller than that of a molybdenum-oxo complex that shows a maximum of 1600 moles of H2 per mole of catalyst per hour at an overpotential of 642mV [21]. In order to determine whether complex 1 retains activity over longer time periods, two 72-h controlled-potential experiments at −1.45V vs Ag/AgCl were conducted in stirred 0.25M phosphate buffer solutions, pH 7.0, containing the catalyst at 6.52μM concentration at 25°C and −20°C. As shown in Fig. S12, at 25°C, the catalyst affords a robust and essentially linear charge build-up over time, with no substantial loss in activity over the course of 72h. A total of 1091C was passed during the electrolysis, which is much higher than that at −20°C (Fig. S13). 4 Conclusion We have successfully prepared a dinuclear copper(I) complex 1, a new molecular catalyst by the reaction of CuI and 1-[(2-methoxy) benzene]-3-[2-(chloro)benzene] triazene. Electrochemical studies showed that 1 can generate hydrogen not only from acetic acid but from water without use of additional acids. Our ongoing efforts are focused on modifying ligands to give related water-soluble complexes for further functional studies, with an emphasis on chemistry relevant to sustainable energy cycles. coredata.dc:description: The reaction of 2-chloroaniline and o-anisidine afforded a new triazenido ligand, 1-[(2-methoxy) benzene]-3-[2-(chloro)benzene] triazene (HL). In the presence of Et3N, the reaction of HL and CuI gave a triazenide complex {Cu2(L)2} 1, a new molecular electrocatalyst, which has been determined by X-ray crystallography. The CuCu distance of 2.4764(8) Å is significantly shorter than the sum of the van der Waals radii of Cu (1.40Å). Electrochemical studies indicated that the catalyst can catalyze hydrogen evolution from both acetic acid with a turnover frequency (TOF) of 65 (in DMF) moles of hydrogen per mole of catalyst per hour at an overpotential of 942mV and neutral buffer (pH 7.0) with a TOF of 324 moles of hydrogen per mole of catalyst per hour at an overpotential of 939mV vs SHE, respectively. Sustained proton reduction catalysis occurs at glassy carbon (GC) to give H2 over a 72h electrolysis period with 97% Faradaic yield and no observable decomposition of the catalyst.
coredata.dc:title: A new copper(I)–triazenido electro-catalyst for catalyzing hydrogen evolution from acetic acid and water
